<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: SANDERS SHOULD JOIN THE NFL, FATHER SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The father of Barry Sanders, Oklahoma State's Heisman Trophy winner, said that 
his son should forgo his senior year at Oklahoma State, which is under National 
Collegiate Athletic Assn. sanction, and try his luck in the National Football 
League. 
</P>
<P>
"If he won the Heisman Trophy again this year, he couldn't get any more money 
or market himself any more than they are already," William Sanders said. 
</P>
<P>
Barry Sanders said in early January, when a four-year probation for Oklahoma 
State's football program was announced, that he would return for his senior 
season with the Cowboys. 
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Sanders said he has made a decision but wouldn't say what it is. 
</P>
<P>
The Dallas Morning News reported Sunday, however, that Sanders, a junior, told 
one NFL team that he will definitely turn professional. Since Sanders has never 
redshirted, he would not be eligible for the regular NFL draft this spring 
unless he decides to challenge it in the courts. He could, however, apply for 
the summer supplemental draft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
