<HEADLINE>
<P>
GM TO SPLIT STOCK, RAISE DIVIDEND; 
</P>
<P>
MOVES DESIGNED TO SIGNAL CONFIDENCE, ANALYSTS SAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
General Motors Corp. on Monday raised its dividend 20% and declared a 
two-for-one stock split in a move analysts said showed the auto maker's 
confidence in its near-term profits. 
</P>
<P>
The quarterly dividend per common share will be lifted to $1.50 from $1.25 a 
share, making the annual dividend $6 a share. The two-for-one stock split will 
take place later, and the dividend payment will be adjusted to reflect the 
split. 
</P>
<P>
GM also said it raised the payout on its Class E stock, which is based on the 
performances of its Electronic Data Systems Corp. unit, and on its Class H 
stock, based on the GM Hughes Electronics subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
GM disclosed in December that it is holding talks with the Howard Hughes 
Medical Institute, which owns 86% of GM's Class H shares, to help meet the 
institute's need for additional liquidity. A GM spokesman said Monday that he 
did not know whether the increase in the dividend was part of a settlement on 
that issue with the medical institute. 
</P>
<P>
GM had paid a $5-a-share common stock dividend on an annual basis since 1984. 
The increase in the dividend followed Ford Motor Co.'s decision last month to 
increase its payout by 25% to $3 a share on an annual basis. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it's designed to signal confidence," said analyst Joseph Phillippi of 
Shearson Lehman Hutton. "This is the board talking, and it's a signal that they 
are confident that things are getting better." 
</P>
<P>
He noted that some analysts expected GM to raise its dividend by only 10%. 
</P>
<P>
Analyst Ronald Glantz of Montgomery Securities said that while he expected a 
dividend increase, he was surprised that GM raised the payout so early in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
"This suggests that investors will be pleased with fourth-quarter earnings," 
Glantz said. 
</P>
<P>
The action means that GM's dividend yield on its common stock is 6.7%, compared 
to 5.5% at Ford and 3.6% at Chrysler. 
</P>
<P>
GM Chairman Roger B. Smith has repeatedly said that GM will post record net 
earnings for 1988. The auto maker turned in surprising record profit for the 
third quarter and is expected to report strong results next week for the fourth 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
However, GM began 1989 with soft auto sales that were down 11% in January from 
year-ago levels. The auto maker, like its U.S. competitors, has had to offer 
incentives, including cut-rate financing programs, to reduce its abnormally 
high inventories. 
</P>
<P>
Analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert said GM will have no trouble 
paying the additional dividend, which will cost it $300 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
The company increased the dividend on Class E stock, representing the GM 
Electronic Data Systems Corp. earnings, by 41% to 24 cents a share. The Class H 
dividend, based on the Hughes division earnings, was raised 64% to 18 cents a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
GM also reversed one of its most unpopular decisions Monday, saying that it is 
restoring vision and hearing benefits to about 190,000 U.S. salaried employees 
and their families effective March 1. 
</P>
<P>
The auto maker said its increased profitability allowed it to respond to 
employee and retiree concerns and to restore the benefits, which were taken 
away last year. 
</P>
<P>
GM's decision to end fully paid vision and hearing coverage sparked protests by 
GM workers, some of whom picketed last year's annual shareholders' meeting. 
</P>
<P>
At the time, the auto maker said it could not afford to continue the benefits, 
which it said were particularly expensive in the case of older workers and 
retirees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
