<HEADLINE>
<P>
GRIPES ABOUT AIRLINES RISE 50% IN JANUARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consumer complaints against major airlines rose 50% in January and airlines 
reported increases in late flights and mishandled baggage at the end of last 
year, but on-time performance was still well ahead of a year earlier, a 
government report said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The Transportation Department, in its monthly consumer report on air travel, 
said consumer complaints against the industry reported to the department went 
from 724 in December -- the lowest level in four years -- to 1,086 in January. 
But the new total was still a 70% improvement over the 3,674 complaints 
received in January, 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Complaints covered a wide variety of problems, including flight cancellations, 
ticketing mistakes, difficulty in getting refunds, lost baggage, rude 
employees, problems with smoking restrictions and claims of misleading 
advertising. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
More Mishandled Baggage 
</P>
<P>
The nation's 13 largest domestic carriers reported that 76.1% of their flights 
were on time in December, compared to 77.7% a month earlier. The rate was still 
nearly 10 points better than December, 1987, when one-third of all flights were 
late. 
</P>
<P>
A department news release blamed the busy Christmas-New Year holiday season for 
an increase in mishandled baggage reports filed against the carriers in 
December. The reports averaged 8.58 for each 1,000 passengers, compared to 6.17 
in November. 
</P>
<P>
The airlines covered in the monthly consumer report account for about 90% of 
domestic flight revenue. Carriers are required to report on operations in and 
out of the nation's 27 largest airports. 
</P>
<P>
For the third month in a row, Eastern Airlines reported the best on-time 
record, with 88.1% of its flights arriving within 15 minutes of posted time. 
Earlier this year, Eastern was consistently among airlines with the most 
delayed flights. The figures do not count fights delayed because of mechanical 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
Eastern was followed by Southwest, with 79.6% on time, and Delta, with 79.3%. 
</P>
<P>
Piedmont had the worst record for mishandled baggage, 12.27 for each 1,000 
passengers, and Southwest had the best, 4.59 for each 1,000. 
</P>
<P>
Pan American had the most ticketed passengers denied seats on overbooked 
flights, with 10.54 for each 10,000 boardings for the first nine months of 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
ON-TIME PERFORMANCE 
</P>
<P>
Percentage of flights in December arriving on time. That is defined as arriving 
within 15 minutes of the scheduled time. 
</P>
