<P>
 LOW TURNOUT IN 50TH DISTRICT EXPECTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Candidates are working to get out the votes for today's special election for a 
vacant seat in the 50th Assembly District. Turnout is expected to be low. 
</P>
<P>
Campaign consultants said turnout could be as low as 15% for the rare February 
special election in the district encompassing Inglewood, El Segundo, 
Westchester, Lennox and parts of South-Central Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
The election pits Curtis Tucker Jr., son of the late Assemblyman Curtis R. 
Tucker (D-Inglewood), against Democrats Lois Hill-Hale and Carl McGill and 
Republican Mike Davis. 
</P>
<P>
Tucker is regarded as the favorite because of name recognition, a large 
fund-raising lead and backing by state Democratic leaders. The special election 
was called when the elder Tucker won a posthumous reelection victory in 
November, a month after his death from cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
