<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR BODY: COLD-WEATHER EXERCISERS NEED TO EASE INTO THEIR ROUTINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KATHLEEN DOHENY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cold-weather exercisers should increase their warm-up time to decrease injury 
risk, being careful to warm the entire body before stretching major muscle 
groups, exercise specialists say. 
</P>
<P>
Colder weather makes muscles more prone to injury, according to Dr. Ronald 
Mackenzie, medical director of Centinela National Athletic Health Institute in 
Culver City. The traditional "tree lean" -- in which exercisers lean against a 
tree or wall to stretch leg muscles -- isn't sufficient pre-exercise warm-up 
and should never be done first, he added. 
</P>
<P>
Spend time warming up the entire body, advised Cindy Baily, a Santa Monica 
physical therapist. "Shift your weight from side to side, for instance, and 
pump your arms." She recommends the overall body warm-up in any weather and 
suggests lengthening it from one minute to two in cold weather "to get blood 
flowing to major muscle groups before you stretch them." Mackenzie's alternate 
suggestion for an overall body warm-up: "Step into hip-deep Jacuzzi water for 
five minutes and walk around." 
</P>
<P>
Next, concentrate on slowly stretching specific muscles, said Bailey, paying 
particular attention to those on the front and back of the thighs and the 
buttocks. In all, spend seven to 10 minutes warming up, he advised. 
</P>
<P>
Latchkey Kids, Health 
</P>
<P>
Latchkey kids aren't ill any more often than their counterparts in 
adult-supervised care, nor is their self-esteem usually lower, researchers in 
two separate studies have concluded. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Rickey Williams of the University of Arizona Health Sciences Center in 
Tucson and Dr. W. Thomas Boyce of the UC San Francisco Medical Center studied 
503 Tucson fifth-graders over a two-year period and found latchkey kids no more 
likely to be obese than other children, nor more likely to miss school or visit 
the school health office. 
</P>
<P>
The study, reported in the American Journal of Diseases of Children, was 
prompted by medical reports indicating that latchkey kids may be more stressed 
and that stress, in turn, might affect their physical health. 
</P>
<P>
In a separate study, Dr. Brad D. Berman of Children's Hospital in Oakland and 
an assistant clinical professor of pediatrics at UC San Francisco studied 
fourth- and sixth-graders in three Bay Area schools, separating them into four 
groups: self-care, home-care by parents or other adults, older-sibling care, or 
out-of-home day care. "Kids in self-care didn't have any lower self-esteem than 
kids in adult care. But unexpectedly, kids in older-sibling care did have lower 
self-esteem compared with the other three groups," said Berman, who presented 
his findings Monday at the western regional meeting of the Ambulatory 
Pediatrics Assn. 
</P>
<P>
The researchers acknowledged that the optimal arrangement of adult-supervised 
care is not always available or affordable. If children must stay alone, Boyce 
said, "it's important for kids to know how they can get in touch with a parent 
and to know safety procedures such as how to answer the door and the 
telephone." 
</P>
<P>
Said Dr. Keitha Scott, a pediatrician at Kaiser Permanente Los Angeles Medical 
Center: "Kids in self-care (at age 11) probably aren't sicker. But I worry more 
about their emotional health and physical security than about obesity or visits 
to the nurse." 
</P>
<P>
Travel and Pregnancy 
</P>
<P>
Healthy pregnant women can usually travel safely if they follow some 
common-sense precautions, conclude two physicians writing in the current 
Journal of the American Medical Assn. 
</P>
<P>
"Try to get immunizations up to date before pregnancy," said Dr. Frank Bia, an 
associate professor of medicine at Yale University School of Medicine who 
co-authored the report with Dr. Michelle Barry, also a Yale associate professor 
of medicine. "And stay out of areas where there is chloroquine-resistant 
malaria," Bia advised, citing Thailand and the Amazon region as locations to 
avoid. 
</P>
<P>
Among their other advice: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Don't plan air travel late in pregnancy. "Domestic airline regulations 
stipulate that air travel for pregnant women after 36 weeks' gestation is not 
allowed and most foreign airlines have a cutoff of 35 weeks' gestation," 
according to Bia and Barry. 
</P>
<P>
 -- To reduce the risk of phlebitis (vein inflammation), walk around as 
frequently as possible during air travel, Bia suggested. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Forget high-altitude trekking. "Prolonged exposure of pregnant women to the 
high altitudes beyond (15,000 feet) achieved on many commercial treks has not 
been studied, and caution should be exercised," the doctors write. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Skiers and other cold-weather exercisers need to increase their warm-up 
time to decrease risk of injury, exercise specialists say. BRIAN GADBERY / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
