</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020789-0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 15433 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 7, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part 5; Page 1; Column 2; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
2023 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEALTH; 
</P>
<P>
SHADOW OF A DOUBT; 
</P>
<P>
A SCIENTIST'S PAINFUL LESSON IN THE HUMAN DYNAMICS OF PRENATAL TESTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN PARACHINI, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Until January of last year, Susan Hodge, a biomathemetician and geneticist at 
the UCLA School of Medicine, had been accustomed to teaching prospective 
doctors the fine points of prenatal genetic testing, she recalls, in 
academically detached fashion. 
</P>
<P>
That was before she attempted, at age 40, what was to be her third pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
She and her geneticist husband, David Greenberg, already had two lively 
daughters -- 7 and 10. Both had been healthy babies but it required no academic 
expertise for Hodge and Greenberg to realize this pregnancy was different. 
</P>
<P>
Hodge's age put her in the high-risk category for genetic defects. Prenatal 
evaluation -- the couple chose amniocentesis, performed in Hodge's 17th week -- 
was, as they perceived things, essential. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Lesson in Human Dynamics 
</P>
<P>
But in the weeks between the time she first realized she was pregnant and when 
the test results were delivered, Hodge says today, she was to learn a great 
deal about the human dynamics of genetic testing. None of what she was to find 
out, she says, is included in the medical educations of most doctors. 
</P>
<P>
As she recalled recently, Hodge kept silent about her pregnancy except in the 
presence of her closest friends and family members. "I had just noticed that 
other friends or colleagues, when they (were going to) have amnio, didn't 
announce their (pregnancies) until the day or week they got the result." 
</P>
<P>
Eventually, when Hodge reflected on her behavior to draft a letter -- largely 
written when she was still pregnant -- to the New England Journal of Medicine, 
she concluded: "The other, more disturbing phenomenon is how waiting has 
affected my attitude toward the pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
"At many levels, I deny that I really am pregnant 'until after we get the 
results.' I ignore the flutterings and kicks I feel; I talk of if, rather than 
when the baby comes." 
</P>
<P>
And once the amniocentesis was performed, Hodge said, she found the two weeks 
of waiting for the test results a time of uncontrollable, consuming anxiety and 
fear. 
</P>
<P>
"I (did not anticipate being nearly as anxiety-ridden) as I was. I think it was 
dealing with (the testing process) as a reality rather than (an abstract 
academic concept.)" 
</P>
<P>
She lay awake at night, afraid of what would happen if the test results 
indicated the fetus she was carrying had a serious defect. 
</P>
<P>
"I guess it was just the fear of getting a bad outcome and facing the 
termination of the pregnancy -- a pregnancy that I wanted," she said in a 
quiet, restrained voice over the telephone from New York City, where she and 
Greenberg relocated to new medical school teaching jobs a few months ago. 
</P>
<P>
Although Hodge kept the severity of her emotions at least somewhat to herself, 
"I was losing sleep. I was somewhat distracted." When she did sleep, she wrote 
in her medical journal 
</P>
<P>
letter, her dreams were preoccupied by the need for a second trimester 
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
Greenberg was aware of his wife's anxiety ("She . . . wasn't getting enough 
sleep and was clearly anxious.") but said he did not share it. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, he says today, the possibility the pregnancy could go awry "did not 
enter my consciousness." 
</P>
<P>
"I knew intellectually what the chances were, but I did not accept emotionally 
that it could happen." 
</P>
<P>
As it would turn out, the odds went against the couple. The amniocentesis 
results were among what they considered the worst imaginable. Susan Hodge's 
baby was affected by Down's syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Typical of a Number of Women 
</P>
<P>
According to genetics experts and counselors questioned by The Times -- 
including the counselor whose duties included delivering the bad news to Susan 
Hodge -- Hodge is typical of a growing number of women choosing pregnancy in 
their late 30s or 40s. For such women, Hodge and genetics experts say, the 
perceived need for genetic testing comes to control the entire pregnancy 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
Among the observations: 
</P>
<P>
* The one-, two- or three-week wait for results of amniocentesis or even the 
two-day to one-week wait for results of chorionic villus sampling, a newer and 
slightly different test, can often become a period of intense anxiety. 
</P>
<P>
* Because of pervasive fear that test results will be unfavorable, many women 
-- just as Hodge did -- deliberately restrict the number of people who know of 
their pregnancies to their closest family members and friends. Somehow, they 
reason, if the pregnancy then must be terminated, they will not have to endure 
the emotionally draining experience of explaining the situation to an endless 
variety of acquaintances. In a sense, the pregnancy has less reality if fewer 
people know. 
</P>
<P>
* Until favorable prenatal test results are available that have the effect of 
validating the pregnancy, many women and their spouses refrain from such 
behavior as buying maternity clothing or baby goods and avoid talk that focuses 
on the fetus' behavior. 
</P>
<P>
When she finally decided to go public with her experience -- by writing the 
letter, which was published last month -- Hodge conceded that she had 
effectively suppressed most behavior commonly lumped under the heading of 
</P>
<P>
bonding. But the experience, she and Greenberg say now, became a valuable 
lesson that such denial is actually shortsighted and counterproductive. They 
may make it more -- rather than less -- difficult to cope with a calamitous 
genetic testing result, if it comes. 
</P>
<P>
Chances of a bad result are low. According to Dr. Connie Sandlin, medical 
director of the genetics center at Memorial Medical Center of Long Beach, 
amniocentesis and chorionic villus sampling (commonly known as CVS), return 
favorable findings 95% to 99% of the time. 
</P>
<P>
"I am lucky," said Ann Garber, a genetics testing expert at Cedars-Sinai 
Medical Center, "that 95% of the time in my job, I'm able to give couples 
information that thrills and delights them." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Tension Unavoidable 
</P>
<P>
But for women waiting for their amniocentesis or CVS results, the reality of 
such odds often means very little, Hodge, Greenberg and genetics experts 
agreed. The tension is unavoidable. 
</P>
<P>
"I was in my office talking to a student when the phone rang," Hodge recalled. 
"It was the genetics counselor. 
</P>
<P>
"I said, 'Hold on just a minute,' and asked the student to leave. And I thought 
to myself, 'Good, the waiting is over.' The next words out of his mouth were, 
'I'm sorry, I have bad news.' 
</P>
<P>
"I was simply stunned. I started to ask him (something else) and then I 
realized I wasn't hearing what he was saying." 
</P>
<P>
With a few more formalities, Hodge hung up and dialed her husband. Greenberg 
was writing a difficult research study report and, when the phone rang and he 
heard his wife's voice, he thought she was calling with advice on the wording 
of an especially difficult passage. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Our Baby Is Down's' 
</P>
<P>
"I picked up the phone and (all) she said (was), 'It's Down's,' " Greenberg 
recalled. "She said it in a way that made it sound like the answer to a 
question. I said, 'What?' And she said, 'Our baby is Down's,' and I didn't say 
anything for a long time as I tried to absorb this. (At some point), I said, 
'Oh.' " 
</P>
<P>
Within a few days, the couple arranged for a second-trimester abortion -- the 
solution chosen, genetics counselors said, by 90% or more of those in that 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
Because CVS can be performed earlier in a pregnancy than amniocentesis, 
abortions it precedes usually occur in the first trimester. First-trimester 
abortions are clinically safer and easier to perform than those in the second 
trimester, and they tend to entail less psychological trauma, genetics 
counselors agree. 
</P>
<P>
As their lives regained order, Hodge and Greenberg came to realize that the 
denials and emotional tricks they employed to deny the reality of the pregnancy 
until the amniocentesis validated it had been mistaken. And in this reaction 
the couple have a valuable lesson for others, said Stephen Keiles, the Kaiser 
Foundation Hospital genetics counselor to whom the responsibility to notify 
Hodge fell. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Avoid Dealing With It 
</P>
<P>
"In my experience, the majority of women voice some concerns regarding the 
results (of genetic testing), and I've noticed that a lot of people will not 
want to address certain questions until the results come back," Keiles said. 
"They (couples) say, 'We'll deal with that if we have to.' " 
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, Keiles said, many such couples behave in the fashion of 
Hodge and Greenberg. "One of the most common things I've noticed is people not 
telling others that they are pregnant. I think that is a common theme. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't advise them who they should tell and who they shouldn't, but I . . . 
try to point out that, if the results do indicate a problem, denying the fact 
that there was a pregnancy is not going to make it any easier to deal with. I 
say, 'No matter what you think now, if the results show there is a problem, you 
will be just as upset if you don't tell people as if you do.' " 
</P>
<P>
This is advice that Hodge and Greenberg suggest couples should listen to. All 
of it, she said, has changed her thinking fundamentally. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Enjoy the Pregnancy' 
</P>
<P>
"I would suggest to women who are having prenatal diagnosis that they not try 
to keep the pregnancy a secret," she said, "any longer than they would if they 
were not having prenatal diagnosis. 
</P>
<P>
"Internally, I would suggest that they try to go ahead and enjoy the pregnancy, 
accept it, get excited about it, buy maternity clothes and all the things that 
one does. We thought (that by handling it as we did), we would save ourselves 
pain if we did get a bad outcome. But I felt we had not saved ourselves any 
pain and all we had done was deprived ourselves of the joy." 
</P>
<P>
Greenberg's feelings are identical. "I think it was a mistake for us not to 
admit the pregnancy, not to accept it between ourselves and to keep it 
tentative, as though one could put off the emotional attachment until one was 
certain," he said. "That was just wrong." 
</P>
<P>
Not everyone agrees. Maritchou Jannsen, who heads a group called Support for 
Prenatal Decisions, based in San Bernardino, asserted that it is not possible 
to establish hard and fast rules. 
</P>
<P>
"I think Sue (Hodge) was trying to speak philosophically when she says that, 
another time, they would go right ahead and tell everyone," Jannsen said. "Not 
everybody can deal with outsiders' reactions quite as easily." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Experience Is Common 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach Memorial's Sandlin said the experience of Hodge and Greenberg is 
common. "I think women often aren't even aware that they are reacting in this 
fashion," Sandlin said. And she said that, in the average busy obstetrician's 
office, such subtleties may be easily overlooked by a physician intent on 
monitoring and maintaining the strictly physical health of his patient. 
</P>
<P>
Research studies have shown that both amniocentesis and CVS produce anxiety 
reactions in women undergoing the procedures. But, since the waiting time for 
CVS is shorter and it can be done earlier, the studies found the anxiety for 
CVS to be less than for amniocentesis. But both studies also noted that CVS 
carries a higher risk of spontaneous abortion. And in some patients, other 
experts said, CVS results may not be as reliable as those from amniocentesis. 
</P>
<P>
Cedars-Sinai's Garber said that, strictly on the narrow issue of emotional 
effects, she prefers CVS, especially since its timing permits the abortion 
decision to be made before a woman's pregnancy starts to become noticeable to 
others. 
</P>
<P>
"The matter can be kept more private," she said. "If you elect to terminate, it 
is not as obvious to your friends and colleagues." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Choices Are Complex 
</P>
<P>
But Garber and other experts agreed that the choice between CVS and 
amniocentesis is a complex one, based on many factors that can sometimes 
conflict. Generally, these experts agreed, neither procedure can be called 
better than the other. 
</P>
<P>
For Susan Hodge, it took two months to overcome the emotional impact brought 
about by the outcome of her pregnancy and what she now recognizes as her own 
incorrect decisions during its course. 
</P>
<P>
She realized the emotional ordeal was over at a certain, quite specific moment. 
"I was able to laugh very hard at something my daughter said," she recalled, 
"and then I started crying." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Before they can peacefully bond with their unborn children, many women 
endure the intense anxiety of waiting for genetic testing results. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
WOMEN -- HEALTH; PREGNANCY; DIAGNOSTIC TESTS; GENETICS; AMNIOCENTESIS; 
EMOTIONS; ABORTION; GENETIC DISEASES; PSYCHOLOGY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020789-0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 15434 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 7, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part 5; Page 1; Column 4; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
762 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEALTH; 
</P>
<P>
BOOK REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
BENEFITS OF SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH: THE AWARENESS AND THE WARINESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE DEMBART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Genethics: The Clash Between the New Genetics and Human Values by David Suzuki 
and Peter Knudtson (Harvard University Press: $25; 384 pages) 
</P>
<P>
The theme is an old one. Science for good and science for evil. It recurs in 
literature, in thought and in reality. Unfortunately, there is no solution, 
only a warning: Be aware and beware. 
</P>
<P>
Until this century, science for evil, while recognized, seemed an aberration. 
Since World War II, we have known that it is more than that. The destructive 
power of knowledge is at least as great as its positive applications. The two 
are inseparably linked. 
</P>
<P>
Microbiology is the latest discipline to discover that science is a two-edged 
sword. The explosion of knowledge in the last several decades into the chemical 
basis of life has opened vast possibilities for use and for abuse. What to do 
about it is the subject of "Genethics: The Clash Between the New Genetics and 
Human Values" by David Suzuki and Peter Knudtson, a book that offers more 
questions than answers. 
</P>
<P>
Biotechnology has been a controversial subject since the early 1970s, when the 
techniques of genetic engineering were first developed. Mindful of the dilemma 
that the atomic scientists of World War II had created, biologists feared 
unleashing a new uncontrollable weapon on the world. 
</P>
<P>
Specifically, they were concerned that a genetically engineered organism could 
escape from a laboratory and wreak havoc, and, for the first time in the 
history of science, they voluntarily adopted a moratorium on research until the 
potential for such a catastrophe could be assessed. 
</P>
<P>
Having assured themselves -- and many of the rest of us -- that the possibility 
was remote, they resumed and expanded their work. Now the question is a 
different and much more fundamental one: Regardless of the potential benefits, 
is it wise to tinker with the essence of life? 
</P>
<P>
"As we embark on this new era of applied molecular genetics, we are in some 
ways incredibly shortsighted," Suzuki and Knudtson warn. "We are so intent on 
rushing to exploit our newly acquired insights that we often do not have the 
faintest idea of the long-term consequences of our technologies." 
</P>
<P>
Genetic research makes possible the creation of new forms of life. The authors 
concede the potential benefits of manufacturing new medicines and repairing 
genetic defects. But they fear that "repairing genetic defects" sounds a lot 
like "improving the race," a slogan that has already been used and could still 
be used for great harm. 
</P>
<P>
And, in an echo of the earlier concern about the escape of pathological new 
organisms, the authors fear that some unknown, unforeseen consequence is still 
lurking in genetic engineering. 
</P>
<P>
"When science creates new technological tools, they often yield instant social 
and financial rewards," they write. "But these successes can blind us to the 
fact that science seldom has much to say about the possible future effects of 
these applications on our societies and ecosystems. We need look no farther 
than the long-term effects of the automobile, nuclear fission, oral 
contraceptives, agricultural pesticides or television to appreciate the myopia 
of science. The effects of each of these applications of science extend far 
beyond the immediate uses for which they were intended." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Answers in Morality 
</P>
<P>
Go slow, the authors urge. We don't know what we're doing. The answers to these 
questions lie in morality, not in science, in wisdom, not in knowledge. They 
call for new ethical principles, which, the authors say, should be drawn from 
as many and wide-ranging sources as possible. 
</P>
<P>
Who can quarrel with such a noble sentiment? On the other hand, is it moral to 
refuse to cure a genetic defect today because of the fear that the knowledge 
will be misused tomorrow? 
</P>
<P>
No one has yet figured out a solution to this problem, and no one is likely to. 
In some sense, it is the problem of modern society. We want -- we need -- the 
benefits of science. We cannot feed ourselves without every technological trick 
at hand. There are too many people on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
By definition, no one knows what the unforeseen problems of knowledge will be 
in the long run. But we cannot give up the short-term benefits. We cannot let 
go of the tiger's tail. 
</P>
<P>
Suzuki, a scientist, and Knudtson, a science writer, are right to point out the 
hazards and to urge and reurge that we treat knowledge of the chemistry of life 
with awe. But can we really turn our backs on this technology? Should we? 
</P>
<P>
Should the printing press have been banned at the outset because one day Hitler 
would publish "Mein Kampf"? 
</P>
</TEXT>
