<HEADLINE>
<P>
GORBACHEV URGED TO DRASTICALLY ALTER ECONOMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL PARKS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's principal economic advisers proposed 
radical changes Monday, including a 30% cut in the Soviet defense budget, in an 
effort to restore popular faith in Gorbachev's reform program. 
</P>
<P>
Abel G. Aganbegyan, secretary of the economic section of the Soviet Academy of 
Sciences, called on the government to spend a quarter of its foreign earnings 
to import Western consumer products and to cancel dozens of major industrial 
projects and use the money for new housing. 
</P>
<P>
Aganbegyan, writing in the Communist Party newspaper Pravda, called for an 
intensive three- to four-year effort to satisfy widespread expectations, so far 
unfulfilled, that perestroika -- as Gorbachev's political and economic reforms 
are known -- would bring a better life. 
</P>
<P>
"Most Soviet families are not feeling changes for the better," he said, 
acknowledging that the resulting disappointment is building into a serious 
political problem for the Soviet leadership. "On paper, we have been taking one 
step forward, but in practice we have been going back two steps." 
</P>
<P>
Going boldly beyond most other reform economists, Aganbegyan urged a massive 
effort to satisfy consumer demand, which greatly outstrips supplies for 
everyday necessities and for luxury goods, in order to build confidence in the 
reforms and to spur faster economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Video Recorders, Computers 
</P>
<P>
Aganbegyan sees in the pent-up demand for consumer goods -- particularly luxury 
items such as videotape recorders, personal computers, high-quality furniture 
and passenger cars -- a way of accelerating economic growth -- 4.4% last year 
compared to the planned 6.6% -- and building the political as well as economic 
momentum needed for reform. 
</P>
<P>
The whole Soviet economy is changing too slowly, Aganbegyan said. The technical 
level of production and the quality of Soviet products have improved only a 
little despite the reforms of the past four years, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to go two or three times faster," he said of the effort to 
restructure the Soviet economy. For example, passenger car production, now 
about 1.8 million vehicles a year, should be increased by 2 million to 3 
million annually, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The urgency with which Aganbegyan views the need to bolster popular confidence 
in the reforms, as well as his desire to foster an economic takeoff, takes him 
well beyond the proposals offered by other reform economists and the positions 
taken by Gorbachev himself in the debate on the country's economic strategy. 
</P>
<P>
Where Gorbachev has announced a 14% reduction in military spending, Aganbegyan 
calls for a 30% cut so that the savings can be used in the civilian sector. 
</P>
<P>
Where other reform economists are suggesting that some foreign loans might be 
used to purchase as much as $7 billion in Western consumer goods over two or 
three years, Aganbegyan proposes doubling such purchases so that they 
constitute at least 25% of all Soviet imports. He calls for cutting back on the 
purchase of machinery to make this possible. 
</P>
<P>
And where others have questioned the immediate need for some of the major 
development projects, Aganbegyan demands the immediate cancellation of two 
giant hydroelectric plants and several massive new irrigation canals, along 
with any other project that cannot quickly pay for itself. He also urges the 
closure of money-losing state enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
"The principal problem is to meet people's demands," Aganbegyan wrote in 
Pravda, "but the measures should not be administrative -- quite a new approach 
is needed to expand independence (of enterprises) and abolish directive-type 
planning." 
</P>
<P>
But Aganbegyan, once the leading proponent of major price reform as the key to 
fundamental economic reform, urged the government to postpone for three or four 
years any effort to restructure the Soviet price system. He had earlier 
insisted that these changes, essential if market forces are to play the larger 
role advocated by most reform economists, be completed by 1991. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Major Implications 
</P>
<P>
If Aganbegyan's proposal is accepted by Gorbachev, it would stretch out the 
overall economic reform effort and have major political and social 
implications. 
</P>
<P>
"The main thing now is to take measures to make the ailing economic mechanism 
healthy," he said, arguing that the country is not prepared for the fundamental 
shifts he believes are needed. 
</P>
<P>
Market-driven growth could be "a powerful engine for the renewal and 
improvement of the whole economy," he continued, but it would require a number 
of support measures, including the large-scale shift of resources now 
controlled by government ministries and state enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
Another major economic goal of his proposal is to reduce inflation, widely 
estimated at 6% to 7% but potentially much more than that, by meeting the 
demand for high-cost items. At the same time, he hopes to cut the government's 
budget deficit through the profits brought in by the sale of the new products. 
</P>
<P>
In his proposal, one of several put forward by leading Soviet economists in 
recent weeks, Aganbegyan dodges responsibility for the failure of Gorbachev's 
initial reforms -- of which he was the principal architect -- to fulfill the 
implicit promise of a better life. 
</P>
<P>
The country's economic stagnation is even deeper than he and other specialists 
had realized, Aganbegyan said, and resistance to the reforms is greater than 
anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
As they have been implemented, he said, the reforms are largely half-measures 
and not radical enough to transform the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
