</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
RETAINS CONFIDENCE IN TOWER DESPITE RUMORS, BUSH SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN M. BRODER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush said Monday that he retains confidence in John Tower as his 
nominee for secretary of defense and that the controversy over the former Texas 
senator's private life would not cripple his ability to handle the Pentagon 
job. 
</P>
<P>
The Senate Armed Services Committee has held up Tower's confirmation while the 
FBI investigates new allegations of excessive drinking and womanizing. In the 
course of its renewed inquiry over the weekend, FBI agents turned up additional 
charges of personal misconduct by Tower, but they could not be substantiated, 
sources said. 
</P>
<P>
Bush was briefed Monday on the progress of the FBI investigation and told 
reporters at an afternoon press conference that he has heard nothing that would 
shake his confidence in Tower. 
</P>
<P>
"I think people would not want a person to step aside, given rumor, 
particularly if the rumor is baseless," Bush said. " . . . If these allegations 
prove to be allegations without fact behind them, I think the people are going 
to say: 'Wait a minute, what went on here?' " 
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that "if someone comes up with facts" indicating that Tower 
is unfit to serve in government, he is not too "narrow-minded" to listen to 
them. 
</P>
<P>
The FBI report is virtually complete but has not been forwarded to the Armed 
Services Committee, sources said. No date has been set for a vote on the 
nomination, but panel Chairman Sam Nunn (D-Ga.) said Monday evening that a vote 
today is unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
The full Senate probably will not receive the nomination until next week. 
</P>
<P>
Bush said that, if Tower is approved, as he expects, he does not believe that 
"there's any danger to his credibility or his ability to do his job." 
</P>
<P>
Some Democrats in Congress, notably House Armed Services Committee Chairman Les 
Aspin of Wisconsin, have said that the flurry of rumors about Tower and the 
protracted confirmation process will leave him weakened and unable to 
effectively take charge at the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
Tower was said Monday to be confident that he will be confirmed. He spent the 
day at the Pentagon working on budget and policy issues with aides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
POLITICAL APPOINTMENTS; POLITICAL ENDORSEMENTS; BUSH, GEORGE; TOWER, JOHN; 
RUMORS; MORALITY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020789-0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 15471 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 7, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part 1; Page 19; Column 1; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
251 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
5TH-GAME DRAW GIVES KARPOV CHESS VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Anatoly Karpov of the Soviet Union drew the fifth game of his quarterfinal 
Candidates chess match against Johann Hjartarson of Iceland in Seattle. By 
drawing, Karpov won the best-of-six-game match, 3 1/2-1 1/2. The sixth game 
will not be played. 
</P>
<P>
The Candidates matches are a series of knockout matches conducted by the World 
Chess Federation to choose a challenger to world champion Gary Kasparov in the 
1990 world chess championship. Karpov, who was world champion from 1975 to 1985 
and is now the world's second-ranked player, advances to the semifinal round. 
He will play his countryman, Artur Yusupov, in a semifinal match, tentatively 
scheduled for this September in London. 
</P>
<P>
Sunday's game repeated the opening moves of the third game, which Karpov had 
won, until move 11, when Hjartarson varied his play. Hjartarson appeared to 
have a slight advantage, but Karpov reached a drawn end game by sacrificing 
first a pawn, and then his queen. 
</P>
<P>
Karpov earned $50,000 for his victory. Hjartarson received $30,000. The match 
was sponsored by Seattle 1990 Goodwill Games. 
</P>
<P>
Here are the moves of the final game: 
</P>
<P>
Hjartarson-Karpov 5, Seattle 1989: 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 Bb5 a6 4 Ba4 Nf6 5 0-0 
Be7 6 Re1 b5 7 Bb3 d6 8 c3 0-0 9 h3 Re8 10 d4 Bb7 11 a4 h6 12 Nbd2 Bf8 13 Bc2 
exd4 14 cxd4 Nb4 15 Bb1 bxa4 16 Rxa4 a5 17 Ra3 Ra6 18 Nh2 g6 19 Ng4 Nxg4 20 
Qxg4 c5 21 dxc5 dxc5 22 e5 Qd4 23 Qg3 Rae6 24 Rae3 c4 25 Bf5 Nd3 26 Bxd3 cxd3 
27 Rxd3 Rxe5 28 Rxd4 Rxe1+ 29 Kh2 Rxc1 30 Nf3 Rc5 31 Rd7 Bxf3 32 Qxf3 Rf5, 
Drawn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
