<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUNGER STRIKER PERSISTS IN BID FOR AIDS MEASURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD C. PADDOCK, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stuart McDonald is in the 36th day of a hunger strike that he has been told 
could hasten his death from AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
But the 33-year-old attorney, who suffers from AIDS-related complex, hopes his 
fast will persuade Gov. George Deukmejian to ban discrimination against 
homosexuals and people who are infected with the deadly virus. 
</P>
<P>
At an emotional press conference in the Capitol on Monday, McDonald vowed to 
continue his fast until the Republican governor reverses his stand and says he 
will sign legislation prohibiting such discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
"I am ready to continue this until he comes out and publicly supports and 
agrees to sign that legislation," McDonald said. "If someone puts their life on 
the line for this, just maybe the governor's heartstrings would be pulled a 
tiny little bit. Maybe that would change his mind." 
</P>
<P>
But Deukmejian, who has acquired a reputation for stubbornness in his dealings 
with the Legislature, is not likely to be moved by McDonald's appeal, aides to 
the governor said. 
</P>
<P>
"We view it as rather unfortunate that Mr. McDonald would be injuring his own 
health for such a misguided reason," said Deukmejian press secretary Kevin 
Brett. "Instead of injuring his own health, he should be saluting the governor 
because California has done more in the fight against AIDS than any other 
state." 
</P>
<P>
He noted that the governor has increased the annual AIDS budget from $3 million 
to $103 million in the last six years. 
</P>
<P>
Brett also said McDonald should file a complaint with the state Department of 
Fair Employment and Housing if he believes he has been a victim of 
discrimination. The agency, Brett said, investigates complaints of 
discrimination against people who have been infected with the AIDS virus even 
if they have no apparent handicap from the disease. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Looking for Work 
</P>
<P>
McDonald told reporters that he had been unable to find a permanent job since 
he tested positive for exposure to the AIDS virus four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
McDonald, who lives in San Francisco and was admitted to the California State 
Bar in 1986, said he had sent out more than 1,000 letters and resumes in search 
of work as an attorney, or even as a law clerk or paralegal. 
</P>
<P>
In his letters, McDonald said he disclosed the fact that he suffers from 
AIDS-related complex, which can sap his strength but still allows him to work a 
40-hour week. The letters brought him two job interviews, but no offers. 
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I did go out and tell employers, all of them, that I have physical 
limitations," he said. "I was very honest about it." 
</P>
<P>
McDonald, upset by his repeated rejection in the job market, began his fast 
Jan. 2, he said. During the hunger strike, he said he has been drinking coffee, 
herbal tea and Gatorade. He has lost 40 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
"My doctor has told me that I will probably come down with AIDS as a result of 
the fast," McDonald said. "I don't want to die. I'd rather be out eating pizza. 
. . . (But) this is probably the most important thing I have ever done in my 
entire life." 
</P>
<P>
McDonald contends that he would not have had such difficulties in finding 
employment if Deukmejian had signed legislation aimed at protecting people who 
are in his predicament. Deukmejian vetoed legislation in 1984 that would have 
prohibited discrimination against homosexuals in employment and housing, 
arguing that there was no compelling evidence of widespread discrimination 
based on sexual orientation. 
</P>
<P>
Last year, the governor vetoed a bill that would have banned discrimination 
against people who have tested positive for the AIDS virus but have not 
developed symptoms of the disease. 
</P>
<P>
In refusing to sign the AIDS measure, Deukmejian said he was not convinced of 
the need for such legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Stuart McDonald Associated Press 
</P>
