<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE PREPS; 
</P>
<P>
GIRLS' ATHLETE OF THE WEEK; 
</P>
<P>
LUNCEFORD'S HELPING FOOT BOOSTS TRABUCO HILLS SOCCER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DONNA CARTER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The leading scorer for Trabuco Hills High School girls' soccer team is a dead 
ringer for Linda Lunceford, who led Esperanza to the 3-A finals last year. 
</P>
<P>
That's because it is Lunceford. 
</P>
<P>
Her family moved from Anaheim to Rancho Santa Margarita because her mother, a 
Methodist minister, was assigned to open a church in the area. 
</P>
<P>
It was as if Lunceford, a junior, had gone from the Space Age to the Stone Age. 
Esperanza is 8-0 in Empire League play and has clinched the league title. 
Trabuco Hills, which was dismal last year, is 3-3 in Pacific Coast League play 
and struggling to make the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
Though mediocre by Esperanza's standard, Trabuco Hills' record is a definite 
improvement over last season. It is due in part to first-year coach Tony 
Cornfoot and Lunceford. 
</P>
<P>
Lunceford, The Times' athlete of the week, leads the Mustangs in scoring with 
29 goals in 15 games. Last Thursday, she scored four goals in a 5-0 victory 
over Laguna Beach. 
</P>
<P>
"She will always score goals because she has a natural instinct to be in the 
right place at the right time," Cornfoot said. 
</P>
<P>
Cornfoot, who coached soccer professionally in England, said Lunceford is one 
of the best girls he has seen and is so powerful that she can strike a ball as 
well as any boy. 
</P>
<P>
As a coach in England, he has seen some good ones. "The English ladies won the 
World Cup in Italy last year, and she could fit into the ladies' English soccer 
team with no problems," Cornfoot said. 
</P>
<P>
Making the transition from Esperanza has been difficult for Lunceford, who was 
an All-Southern Section 3-A soccer team selection as a sophomore. All she has 
known is success. She is an outstanding shortstop for the Ballhawks, the 
third-ranked club softball team in the nation. She also plays for the Shooting 
Stars, the No. 1 club soccer team in California. 
</P>
<P>
"Mainly, I just kept telling myself we'll get better, we'll improve. I just 
felt that I had to work with it," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Things have gotten better. The first half of the season, the Mustangs lost to 
Orange, 6-3. Two weeks ago, Trabuco Hills met Orange again. Orange was 4-0 in 
league play. But Trabuco Hills defeated the Panthers, 2-0, on Lunceford's two 
goals. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
TOP PERFORMERS 
</P>
<P>
Keri Erkenbrack scored 52 points and collected 18 rebounds in two Century 
League victories for Canyon (17-4, 8-0) last week. 
</P>
<P>
Tustin's Teresa Perkins scored 39 points in Sea View League overtime victories 
against Estancia and University last week. She scored the winning basket 
against University. 
</P>
<P>
In a 5-0 victory over Katella, Michelle Rullo scored the hat trick, getting her 
16th, 17th and 18th goals for Esperanza, the No. 2-ranked girls' soccer team in 
4-A. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Linda Lunceford 
</P>
<P>
Trabuco Hills High 
</P>
<P>
Position: Center-forward 
</P>
<P>
Height, Class: 5-6, Junior 
</P>
<P>
Last Week: Scored four goals for the girls' soccer team in Trabuco Hills' 5-0 
victory over Laguna Beach. 
</P>
<P>
Season: Lunceford is the leading scorer for the Mustangs with 29 goals in 15 
games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Linda Lunceford 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
