<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: WHEN DELIVERY RATES INCREASE, SO DOES THE INCOME OF MICRO GENERAL; 
</P>
<P>
SCIENCE/TECHNOLOGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by David Olmos, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Most businesses frown on the idea of higher shipping and mailing costs, but the 
folks over at Micro General Corp. in Irvine smile at such news. 
</P>
<P>
Micro General's business benefits when delivery rates change, as they did 
Monday when general rate increases by United Parcel Service went into effect. 
</P>
<P>
The Irvine company makes computerized shipping systems and postal scales for 
use in shipping departments and office mail rooms. Every time a major shipping 
company, such as UPS or the Postal Service, changes its rates, Micro General 
enjoys a windfall. 
</P>
<P>
The reason is this: The heart of every Micro General product is a tiny computer 
chip on which is stored information about shipping company rates. The 
computerized shipping systems enable a company's mail room, for example, to 
comparison shop among different shipping firms to find the least costly way to 
send a package. 
</P>
<P>
Each time there is a rate change, the microchip must be replaced. In the case 
of the UPS increase, most of Micro General's 15,000 customers will have to pay 
the Irvine firm $115 to order the new chip. 
</P>
<P>
The result, Micro General says, will be a 25% windfall in its revenue for the 
current quarter ending in March. A company spokesman, Charles Ramsey, says the 
firm is not forecasting what its total revenue will be for the period. 
</P>
<P>
Micro General had earnings of $202,668 on revenue of $4.4 million for the 9 
months ended last September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
MICRO GENERAL CORP; SEMICONDUCTORS; SHIPPING; POSTAL RATES 
</P>
