</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: SCIENCE/TECHNOLOGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by David Olmos, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The president and chairman of Standard Logic Inc. has resigned after a dispute 
with company directors over management of the small Anaheim electronics 
manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
Dennis A. Wade resigned Jan. 27. His replacement is Wes Baumgardner, a company 
founder and president and chairman from 1967 to 1987. 
</P>
<P>
The company also said it has canceled a letter of intent to merge with U.S. 
Metals &amp; American Welding Supply, a metal manufacturer in Sandy, Ore. "The 
terms they submitted to us were not acceptable," Baumgardner said. He said 
Standard Logic will continue to seek other merger candidates. 
</P>
<P>
Baumgardner said the differences between Wade and the board coincided with a 
worsening financial picture in November. The company expects to report a loss 
of more than $1 million on revenue of $2.4 million for its fiscal year ended 
Oct. 31. 
</P>
<P>
Baumgardner said the firm is "reevaluating its assets" after a sharp decline in 
sales and new orders in the first quarter ended Jan. 31. Revenue declined 56% 
to $232,000, from $534,000 a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
He said the company has "redirected" its marketing program and hopes to return 
to profitability within 3 months. 
</P>
<P>
Standard Logic, which employed 130 people and had sales of more than $8 million 
in the 1974-75 period, currently has only 13 employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
