<HEADLINE>
<P>
FAIRFAX STORES EMPTIED IN METHANE LEAK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GEORGE RAMOS and BETTINA BOXALL, Times Staff Writers 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 50 commercial buildings in the Fairfax district were evacuated early 
today after potentially explosive levels of methane gas were detected on a 
sidewalk and in the basements of two stores, one of which was shattered by a 
gas explosion in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities expected the evacuation to last all day. To prevent a dangerous 
buildup of gas, firefighters planned to pump ground water from beneath the area 
into the sewer system. Removing the water, officials said, would relieve 
pressure on the gas, which is naturally produced by rotting organic material in 
old oil fields underlying the area. 
</P>
<P>
Workers at a K Mart and Ross Dress for Less Store in a Third Street shopping 
center across from the Farmers Market reported the gas seepage at 6:12 this 
morning. Dangerous levels of methane also were found on the sidewalk in front 
of the Gilmore Bank, as well as in the shopping center. 
</P>
<P>
Several blocks of Third Street between Fairfax Avenue and Gardner Street were 
immediately blocked off. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities attributed the gas threat to the same forces that caused the 1985 
explosion, which injured 21 people. Subterranean methane gas still seeps to the 
surface, where it is trapped by buildings and streets. 
</P>
<P>
"The gas is always looking for a way out of the ground," said Assistant Fire 
Chief Jim Young. The recent rain has compounded the problem by saturating the 
ground and leaving less space for the gas. 
</P>
<P>
"The percolation is quite forceful," said Vince Marzo, another Fire Department 
spokesman. "We'd probably be looking at angels with harps" if a match were 
struck near the area, Marzo said. 
</P>
<P>
After the 1985 blast in the Ross Dress for Less Store in the Parklabrea 
Shopping Center, gas vents were installed beneath the parking lot and in Ross's 
basement. The city has also since required the installation of gas detection 
devices in residential basements and directed commercial building owners to 
meet new ventilation standards in their basements or to install gas detection 
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Firefighters probe for methane gas leak in Farmers Market. BRIAN GADBERY 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
