<P>
JAPAN TIGHTENS SECURITY FOR FUNERAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Air cargo has been banned from all domestic flights in and out of Tokyo's two 
airports for five days around the Feb. 24 funeral of Emperor Hirohito to 
prevent sabotage, transport officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
Transport Ministry officials said airlines and cargo companies were told only 
emergency items such as medicine would be exempt from the ban, set to begin on 
Feb. 22. "We have made the decision in view of the rush of international VIPs 
visiting for the funeral and to guard against bombs or explosive devices which 
may be concealed in air cargo by extremists," a ministry official said. 
</P>
