<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. URGED TO INVEST AT HOME TO CUT DEFICITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States needs to boost its rate of savings and businesses must plow 
more money into plants and equipment if the nation hopes to slash its external 
deficits, economists say. 
</P>
<P>
Progress appears stalled in Washington's battle to reduce the country's trade 
gap and current account deficit, which measure U.S. demand for imports against 
foreign demand for American products. 
</P>
<P>
While the dollar has declined more than 50% in the past three years, making 
U.S. exports more competitive, the currency decline by itself has not reversed 
the imbalances. 
</P>
<P>
The United States must make the following basic changes, economists said in 
interviews this week: 
</P>
<P>
Boost government, personal and corporate savings to reduce the dependence on 
foreign borrowing and free up funds for productive investment. 
</P>
<P>
Bolster investment in plants and equipment to raise productivity, making 
American goods more competitive by lowering costs. 
</P>
<P>
Increase research and development and create new, higher-quality products. 
</P>
<P>
Find new markets for U.S. exports to make up for the loss of demand from Latin 
America, which is burdened by debt, and from the 13 members of the Organization 
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, which are pressured by low oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
Although the Group of Seven industrial nations voiced hopes of reducing global 
trade imbalances at its meeting in Washington Friday, economists are not as 
optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
Efforts to cut the massive U.S. trade deficit, which makes up most of the 
broader current account gap, will be tough, they said. 
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit measures imports against exports, while the current account 
includes "invisible goods" such as shipping, tourism and banking. The 1988 U.S. 
trade deficit was $126 billion through November, while the current account 
shortfall was $135 billion through the 1988 third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Servicing external debt limits the resources the United States has available 
for productive ventures such as factories and thus weighs on present and future 
living standards, economists said. Rising trade deficits increase the country's 
dependence on foreigners, as they are financed by an inflow of capital from 
abroad. 
</P>
<P>
Growing dependence on foreign borrowing is keeping U.S. interest rates high to 
ensure continued foreign investment, economists said. A halt of these funds, 
for any reason, will send the dollar tumbling and interest rates surging. 
</P>
<P>
Washington also has a political stake in balancing its books regarding foreign 
trade. 
</P>
<P>
"The credibility of the U.S. as a world leader was severely undermined when the 
nation turned into the world's largest debtor country with its currency 
constantly under pressure," said Shafiq Islam of the Council on Foreign 
Relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
