<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SUNS FILE PROTEST OVER DOUBLE FOUL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHOENIX 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Phoenix Suns have filed a protest with the NBA, claiming that the referees' 
misinterpretation of a rule cost their club in last Saturday night's overtime 
loss here to Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
With Phoenix trailing 118-116, Suns guard Kevin Johnson collided with Hawks 
guard Doc Rivers on a drive to the basket with 10 seconds remaining in 
overtime. 
</P>
<P>
Referee Ed Rush called a charging foul on Johnson while referee Jim Capers 
called a blocking foul on Rivers. A double-foul was assessed and Phoenix 
retained possession of the ball. Instead of calling a jump ball at center 
court, however, referees instructed Phoenix to inbound the ball, and Johnson's 
desperation jumper at the buzzer bounced off the front of the rim on the final 
play. 
</P>
<P>
The Suns, in their protest Monday, said that the double-foul rule was 
misinterpreted by the referees and that there should have been a jump ball. 
</P>
<P>
Phoenix officials said NBA Commissioner David Stern should make a ruling on the 
protest within five days of receiving the letter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
